HEADWORD: Obeisance
<hw>O*bei"sance</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>ob⟦eacute⟧issance</ets> obedience, fr. <ets>ob⟦eacute⟧issant</ets>.
See <er>Obey</er>, and cf. <er>Obedience</er>,
<er>Abaisance</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Obedience.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Deference or homage, or an expression of deference
or respect; a bow; a curtsy.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><q>Bathsheba bowed and did <qex>obeisance</qex> unto the king.</q>
<rj><qau>1 Kings i. 16.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Obeisancy</ent>⟦br⟧
